messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /cms/user/login

All HTTP methods acceptable:
- No

Allowed methods (based on the code, not on runtime/framework behavior):
- HEAD: No
- POST: Yes
- OPTIONS: No
- TRACE: No
- GET: No
- PUT: No
- DELETE: No
- PATCH: No

Explanation:
- In app/__init__.py the CMS blueprint is registered on the application with url_prefix="/cms".
- In app/api/cms/__init__.py the user blueprint is registered on the CMS blueprint with url_prefix="/user".
- In app/api/cms/user.py the login route is defined as @user_api.route("/login", methods=["POST"]), which makes the full path the concatenation of the prefixes and route: /cms + /user + /login => /cms/user/login.
- The route decorator explicitly lists methods=["POST"], so only POST is accepted according to the source code. Per your instruction, automatic framework behaviors (e.g., implicit HEAD or OPTIONS handling by Flask) are not assumed, so those methods are marked as not acceptable.
